00:01:20.070 --> 00:01:22.560
and help bring about as
many insights as possible

00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:24.640
for you all to consume.

00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:26.310
In framing this
discussion, we can

00:01:26.310 --> 00:01:29.100
think about alternative
models to healthcare reform

00:01:29.100 --> 00:01:31.090
on a spectrum, if you will.

00:01:31.090 --> 00:01:34.206
On one end, there is the
single payer types of policies.

00:01:34.206 --> 00:01:36.330
Again, single payer may
mean many different things.

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:38.100
And I hope we go
into that today.

00:01:38.100 --> 00:01:39.870
It involves
decisions like, who's

00:01:39.870 --> 00:01:42.130
bearing the risk, how
do we pool the risk,

00:01:42.130 --> 00:01:44.700
how do finance the care, how
do we pay for it, would you

00:01:44.700 --> 00:01:46.844
have a fee for service
system under single payer,

00:01:46.844 --> 00:01:49.260
would you have a global payment
system under single payer?

00:01:49.260 --> 00:01:51.180
Those are some of
the nuanced decisions

00:01:51.180 --> 00:01:56.040
under the single payer
end of the spectrum.

00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:58.030
On the other end
of the spectrum,

00:01:58.030 --> 00:02:01.590
we have decisions surrounding
things like, how far do we

00:02:01.590 --> 00:02:04.290
allow, or how much do we
allow private insurance

00:02:04.290 --> 00:02:07.590
companies to help bear the
risk at the expense partially

00:02:07.590 --> 00:02:08.669
of government?

00:02:08.669 --> 00:02:11.820
Decisions such as, how
far do we expand a program

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:15.240
like Medicare Advantage, or
a program like the exchanges,

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:18.210
which operate based
on a private platform?

00:02:18.210 --> 00:02:22.620
Within this spectrum, and in
thinking about the alternative,

00:02:22.620 --> 00:02:24.510
I would like to pose
and encourage you

00:02:24.510 --> 00:02:28.030
to think about three
fundamental questions.

00:02:28.030 --> 00:02:34.310
The first is to what degree is
guaranteed coverage required

00:02:34.310 --> 00:02:37.511
to achieve universal coverage?

00:02:37.511 --> 00:02:41.640
I'd encourage us to think about
the nuances and the differences

00:02:41.640 --> 00:02:46.770
between guaranteed coverage
and universal coverage.

00:02:46.770 --> 00:02:50.940
The second is to what
extent does health insurance

00:02:50.940 --> 00:02:54.800
provide health security?

00:02:54.800 --> 00:02:56.690
Again here, the
nuanced differences

00:02:56.690 --> 00:02:59.810
between having health
insurance and actually having

00:02:59.810 --> 00:03:01.940
health security.

00:03:01.940 --> 00:03:07.010
The third question is how do
we align affordable healthcare

00:03:07.010 --> 00:03:10.380
with acceptable healthcare?

00:03:10.380 --> 00:03:13.800
Again, the nuanced differences
between what is affordable

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:17.470
and what is to us, as
a society, acceptable.

00:03:17.470 --> 00:03:19.530
Now, in thinking about
these three questions,

00:03:19.530 --> 00:03:21.540
I'd simply like
to pose that there

00:03:21.540 --> 00:03:24.030
is a positive way of
thinking about it.

00:03:24.030 --> 00:03:26.400
Positive not from the
good or bad perspective,

00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:30.100
but positive from the positive
or normative perspective.

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:32.100
So to each of these
questions we can think of it

00:03:32.100 --> 00:03:33.808
from a policy standpoint
that is positive

00:03:33.808 --> 00:03:36.480
and from a policy standpoint
that is normative.

00:03:36.480 --> 00:03:40.440
For the first question of the
differences between guaranteed

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:45.420
coverage and universal coverage,
rephrased as what is our path

00:03:45.420 --> 00:03:48.420
to universality, the
positive interpretation

00:03:48.420 --> 00:03:51.120
might be that this is
about a set of regulations

00:03:51.120 --> 00:03:51.970
or requirements.

00:03:51.970 --> 00:03:54.030
So what regulation
or requirement

00:03:54.030 --> 00:03:56.640
would you like,
would one vote for?

00:03:56.640 --> 00:03:58.500
But I would argue that
the normative stance,

00:03:58.500 --> 00:04:00.480
the normative
argument, behind this

00:04:00.480 --> 00:04:05.020
is what is the role of
government in our society?

00:04:05.020 --> 00:04:07.470
I hope our speakers
touch on that today.

00:04:07.470 --> 00:04:09.840
For the second
question, to what extent

00:04:09.840 --> 00:04:12.840
does health insurance
provide health security,

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:14.220
the positive
interpretation might

00:04:14.220 --> 00:04:16.710
be that this is about
actuarial value,

00:04:16.710 --> 00:04:18.209
that when you have
an insurance plan

00:04:18.209 --> 00:04:20.100
it's got to cover
a set of things.

00:04:20.100 --> 00:04:21.870
And how broad is
that set of things

00:04:21.870 --> 00:04:26.670
under the universe of everything
that medicine can provide?

00:04:26.670 --> 00:04:29.850
But the normative side of
this is much more about

00:04:29.850 --> 00:04:35.590
what is the definition of
security in a person's life.

00:04:35.590 --> 00:04:40.052
That's a different question than
the positive interpretation.

00:04:40.052 --> 00:04:41.510
And the third
overall question, how

00:04:41.510 --> 00:04:43.400
do we align
affordable healthcare

00:04:43.400 --> 00:04:46.340
with acceptable
healthcare, affordable

00:04:46.340 --> 00:04:49.820
from a positive standpoint
might center on cost sharing.

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:51.200
What is a person's premium?

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:53.630
What is a person's deductible?

00:04:53.630 --> 00:04:58.690
What is a person's co-insurance
or co-pay at the office?

00:04:58.690 --> 00:05:00.790
But from a normative
standpoint, the differences

00:05:00.790 --> 00:05:04.350
between what's acceptable
and what is affordable

00:05:04.350 --> 00:05:09.290
may center, at the end of
the day, on what is right.

00:05:09.290 --> 00:05:12.040
What is right.

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:14.200
I will close my remarks
there and introduce you

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:16.150
to the first of
