01:15:37.724 --> 01:15:39.390
I want to be a physician
when I'm older.

01:15:39.390 --> 01:15:41.306
And I think I want to
go into health delivery.

01:15:41.306 --> 01:15:43.390
You're all legends.

01:15:43.390 --> 01:15:47.440
Just like thank you very
much for sharing your work.

01:15:47.440 --> 01:15:49.230
First of I'll say
my brother actually

01:15:49.230 --> 01:15:50.546
works for Oscar Health.

01:15:50.546 --> 01:15:53.170
And they're trying to enter the
insurance market in California.

01:15:53.170 --> 01:15:55.290
And a lot of these issues
that you're tackling

01:15:55.290 --> 01:15:57.780
are things they deal with a lot.

01:15:57.780 --> 01:16:00.750
I, myself, I think I'm more
interested in Dr. Doty's

01:16:00.750 --> 01:16:03.930
work, which is international
health systems.

01:16:03.930 --> 01:16:06.180
And I had a pretty specific
question about something.

01:16:06.180 --> 01:16:09.500
You briefly touched on--
and Dr. Song briefly asked--

01:16:09.500 --> 01:16:12.680
and it's about the Netherlands
and also Switzerland.

01:16:12.680 --> 01:16:16.050
Those are two nations that I
feel-- and I'll keep it short--

01:16:16.050 --> 01:16:18.600
they emulate basically
what we have here,

01:16:18.600 --> 01:16:20.655
but they do it
right, like you said.

01:16:20.655 --> 01:16:22.030
You touched on
some of the things

01:16:22.030 --> 01:16:24.624
the Netherlands does well, but
both of those nations, I think,

01:16:24.624 --> 01:16:26.040
are grappling with
what we're also

01:16:26.040 --> 01:16:29.280
grappling, which is an older and
increasingly sicker population,

01:16:29.280 --> 01:16:31.592
and their costs
are rising as well.

01:16:31.592 --> 01:16:33.300
The Switzerland is an
interesting example

01:16:33.300 --> 01:16:35.790
because it's divided into
cantons, which is a little bit

01:16:35.790 --> 01:16:36.670
federalist as well.

01:16:36.670 --> 01:16:38.814
It's similar to the state
structure we have here.

01:16:38.814 --> 01:16:40.980
I was wondering if you, or
others who know about it,

01:16:40.980 --> 01:16:44.260
could comment on specifically
in the short term,

01:16:44.260 --> 01:16:46.010
maybe not in the next
decade, but maybe

01:16:46.010 --> 01:16:48.660
in the next five
years, what are some

01:16:48.660 --> 01:16:51.099
of the things we could take
away from those systems

01:16:51.099 --> 01:16:52.140
and apply them to the US?

01:16:52.140 --> 01:16:53.880
Because I do think
I'm of the mindset

01:16:53.880 --> 01:16:59.340
that rapidly overhauling the ACA
for a full single payer system

01:16:59.340 --> 01:17:03.570
is pretty divisive, and
having to convince 160 people

01:17:03.570 --> 01:17:07.830
currently insured under the
ACA that the increase in taxes

01:17:07.830 --> 01:17:11.190
and potential premiums is better
than the care they already

01:17:11.190 --> 01:17:13.380
receive or the
insurance they have.

01:17:13.380 --> 01:17:19.110
- So what I'll say about
Switzerland and the Netherlands

01:17:19.110 --> 01:17:22.620
is from a delivery system
perspective they all

01:17:22.620 --> 01:17:27.600
embrace the idea that
it's important to care

01:17:27.600 --> 01:17:31.620
about chronic care
management and do it well,

01:17:31.620 --> 01:17:37.260
to care about patients who are
the high need and high cost.

01:17:37.260 --> 01:17:39.630
And they designed
their delivery system

01:17:39.630 --> 01:17:44.620
to take care of that
population really well.

01:17:44.620 --> 01:17:49.300
And that means that
cost sharing is low.

01:17:49.300 --> 01:17:52.260
The primary care
infrastructure is

01:17:52.260 --> 01:17:55.170
designed to address
long term preventive

01:17:55.170 --> 01:17:56.860
care for those populations.

01:17:56.860 --> 01:18:00.810
So they actually are able
to keep the costs down

01:18:00.810 --> 01:18:03.560
for the highest needs
and the high cost.

01:18:03.560 --> 01:18:06.010
So that's one thing.

01:18:06.010 --> 01:18:09.150
The other thing
that they do well

01:18:09.150 --> 01:18:14.850
is really the cost
sharing for low income.

01:18:14.850 --> 01:18:19.590
In Switzerland, they actually
rank with us pretty highly

01:18:19.590 --> 01:18:21.510
on out-of-pocket costs.

01:18:21.510 --> 01:18:23.310
But that high
out-of-pocket cost really

01:18:23.310 --> 01:18:26.040
is for higher
income individuals.

01:18:26.040 --> 01:18:28.850
What sets us apart is
that we have actually

01:18:28.850 --> 01:18:31.590
high out-of-pocket costs for
low and moderate income families

01:18:31.590 --> 01:18:35.647
and other countries
don't do that.

01:18:35.647 --> 01:18:37.730
- Michelle, I'm curious
about this because we do--

01:18:37.730 --> 01:18:41.690
we get this debate
quite a bit actually.

01:18:41.690 --> 01:18:43.310
My understanding
of those systems

01:18:43.310 --> 01:18:49.250
is that the level of government
regulation and public financing

01:18:49.250 --> 01:18:51.600
is quite high.

01:18:51.600 --> 01:18:53.630
And that people think
that these systems

01:18:53.630 --> 01:18:56.049
are the same, but actually
in some fundamentally--

01:18:56.049 --> 01:18:57.590
politically, in some
fundamental way,

01:18:57.590 --> 01:18:59.798
they're very different
because the role of government

01:18:59.798 --> 01:19:04.742
is far beyond what even is
standard in the US, certainly.

01:19:04.742 --> 01:19:06.200
And I wondered if
you could comment

01:19:06.200 --> 01:19:07.200
on that political difference.

01:19:07.200 --> 01:19:08.741
Because it seems
like they're heavily

01:19:08.741 --> 01:19:11.060
regulated systems in that sense.

01:19:11.060 --> 01:19:12.770
- They are.

01:19:12.770 --> 01:19:16.910
I think that the ministers
will have heated debates when

01:19:16.910 --> 01:19:21.530
they're developing
their budgets about how

01:19:21.530 --> 01:19:24.980
the money is going to be
spent throughout the system.

01:19:24.980 --> 01:19:29.900
And I have to say that from
the international perspective

01:19:29.900 --> 01:19:32.480
that they actually
also come to us

01:19:32.480 --> 01:19:37.760
to learn about bundling and
bundle of payments and the ACO

01:19:37.760 --> 01:19:40.340
and lessons learned from there.

01:19:40.340 --> 01:19:42.650
So while I like to say,
oh, we have so much

01:19:42.650 --> 01:19:44.960
to learn from other
countries, that there actually

01:19:44.960 --> 01:19:46.880
is a lot of
cross-fertilization of ideas

01:19:46.880 --> 01:19:51.650
because they are grappling
with how to contain costs

01:19:51.650 --> 01:19:53.780
just as much as we are.

01:19:53.780 --> 01:19:58.220
- Can I throw a sour grape
into this discussion here?

01:19:58.220 --> 01:20:03.770
The countries you mentioned,
Switzerland and Netherlands,

01:20:03.770 --> 01:20:08.960
the highest costs among
affluent countries

01:20:08.960 --> 01:20:13.400
is United States,
more than 17% GDP.

01:20:13.400 --> 01:20:17.240
The second one is Switzerland.

01:20:17.240 --> 01:20:19.710
The third one is
the Netherlands.

01:20:19.710 --> 01:20:22.460
So if you are looking
for efficiency,

01:20:22.460 --> 01:20:25.970
you may not want to do it,
but for practical reasons,

01:20:25.970 --> 01:20:29.770
political reasons, you want
to look at them closely.

01:20:29.770 --> 01:20:31.190
And you are right.

01:20:31.190 --> 01:20:34.880
Netherlands went
through a whole 10 years

01:20:34.880 --> 01:20:41.620
really bring the private
insurance under control.

01:20:41.620 --> 01:20:43.180
Pooling the risk nationwide.

01:20:43.180 --> 01:20:45.850
Before it wasn't.

01:20:45.850 --> 01:20:52.725
And now, you pay the
premium to a central fund.

01:20:52.725 --> 01:20:56.085
The insurance collect the money,
but go to the central fund

01:20:56.085 --> 01:21:01.400
and then reallocated back
with the risk adjustment.

01:21:01.400 --> 01:21:08.060
But also, what they paid to the
providers are highly regulated.

01:21:08.060 --> 01:21:10.800
But they give them some
room for flexibility.

01:21:13.810 --> 01:21:17.470
- So my question here is
given that level of regulation

01:21:17.470 --> 01:21:19.900
and government
control, is that really

01:21:19.900 --> 01:21:22.540
going to generate less
of a political fight

01:21:22.540 --> 01:21:24.306
by the industry interests?

01:21:24.306 --> 01:21:25.430
That's a question, I think.

01:21:32.060 --> 01:21:33.920
- My name is Katherine Arrott.

01:21:33.920 --> 01:21:36.530
And I'm on the board of--

01:21:36.530 --> 01:21:41.990
Massachusetts has 27 regions
to provide in community care

01:21:41.990 --> 01:21:44.450
for the elderly
who are low income.

01:21:47.610 --> 01:21:53.210
If we go back into the
early 2000s when HIV,

01:21:53.210 --> 01:21:54.980
we got our first drugs.

01:21:54.980 --> 01:21:58.940
But they were not affordable
except to the very well off.

01:22:01.560 --> 01:22:07.880
And we wanted to
share those drugs

01:22:07.880 --> 01:22:11.030
with the rest of the world
because they did not have them

01:22:11.030 --> 01:22:13.640
and they could not afford them.

01:22:13.640 --> 01:22:19.370
And so, we approached and we
lobbied the drug companies.

01:22:19.370 --> 01:22:22.070
And they finally
conceded, yes, they

01:22:22.070 --> 01:22:26.210
would consent to selling the
drugs at a much lower price

01:22:26.210 --> 01:22:29.810
provided their patents
were protected.

01:22:29.810 --> 01:22:33.950
So you can reach out to the drug
companies and work with them.

01:22:33.950 --> 01:22:35.030
And I would suggest--

01:22:35.030 --> 01:22:40.270
now, one of the issues is with
the genome having been fully--

01:22:40.270 --> 01:22:42.170
not fully explored--
but that's why

01:22:42.170 --> 01:22:46.910
everybody in the drug
companies are rushing forward

01:22:46.910 --> 01:22:48.680
to develop new drugs.

01:22:48.680 --> 01:22:49.640
That takes money.

01:22:49.640 --> 01:22:52.730
So they've become a
place of great investment

01:22:52.730 --> 01:22:58.020
where there can be tremendous
return if they are successful.

01:22:58.020 --> 01:23:02.690
The drug companies are in
all of the top 10 sections

01:23:02.690 --> 01:23:06.560
of endowments, mutual
funds, and everything else.

01:23:06.560 --> 01:23:10.070
And I think the only way to get
that under control and still

01:23:10.070 --> 01:23:12.860
allow them to get the
investments they need

01:23:12.860 --> 01:23:18.320
to continue their work is to
treat them as a utility and say

01:23:18.320 --> 01:23:23.720
you can have this percentage of
gain to do with what you want,

01:23:23.720 --> 01:23:29.450
but you cannot continue to
raise your drug prices through

01:23:29.450 --> 01:23:32.540
the ceiling because somebody
will pay for it and then

01:23:32.540 --> 01:23:35.660
re-invest in us because
they want to improve

01:23:35.660 --> 01:23:36.590
their endowment.

01:23:36.590 --> 01:23:43.100
I think that's a discussion that
has to be had on a very broad

01:23:43.100 --> 01:23:48.200
across because the times have
changed from how drugs could

01:23:48.200 --> 01:23:49.220
be so successful.

01:23:49.220 --> 01:23:50.640
What do you think?

01:23:57.930 --> 01:24:05.030
- I'm a reader of the
Marcia Angel's books

01:24:05.030 --> 01:24:07.040
on pharmaceutical industry.

01:24:07.040 --> 01:24:10.280
So I have certain bias.

01:24:10.280 --> 01:24:14.430
10 years ago, I did look
at the financial reports

01:24:14.430 --> 01:24:20.100
of the big pharmas,
five major companies.

01:24:20.100 --> 01:24:25.610
The argument that if
you reduce the price,

01:24:25.610 --> 01:24:28.640
or allow regulation
of price, then

01:24:28.640 --> 01:24:31.250
they are going to reduce
their research, to me,

01:24:31.250 --> 01:24:34.460
is a scare tactic.

01:24:34.460 --> 01:24:38.840
If you look at detail what
they spend for marketing,

01:24:38.840 --> 01:24:47.220
advertisement versus how much
they spend really for research,

01:24:47.220 --> 01:24:50.430
they spend equal amount on that.

01:24:50.430 --> 01:24:53.100
And if you look at
the past decade--

01:24:53.100 --> 01:24:56.240
I'm not a student of
the drug industry,

01:24:56.240 --> 01:24:58.010
but I follow a little bit--

01:24:58.010 --> 01:25:01.580
so much of the new inventions
come from small companies,

01:25:01.580 --> 01:25:05.010
and then they buy it.

01:25:05.010 --> 01:25:06.325
So it's not--

01:25:06.325 --> 01:25:13.320
I think, yes, we should be
very careful not to deny-

01:25:13.320 --> 01:25:15.130
to worry about it--

01:25:15.130 --> 01:25:19.050
we do want to keep
innovation and invention.

01:25:19.050 --> 01:25:23.100
But I think the case made
by pharmaceutical companies

01:25:23.100 --> 01:25:24.660
is exaggerated.

01:25:24.660 --> 01:25:26.100
That's my--

01:25:26.100 --> 01:25:27.410
And how do you do it?

01:25:27.410 --> 01:25:29.220
Look at England and Germany.

01:25:29.220 --> 01:25:31.860
They are countries
with big pharma--

01:25:31.860 --> 01:25:35.030
and Switzerland.

01:25:35.030 --> 01:25:37.670
They negotiate with
pharmaceutical companies

01:25:37.670 --> 01:25:39.810
for prices.

01:25:39.810 --> 01:25:44.850
Did that-- so many drugs that
they discover in England.

01:25:44.850 --> 01:25:48.210
England is a major inventor
and production of drugs.

01:25:52.730 --> 01:25:55.730
And England doesn't let
pharmaceutical company just

01:25:55.730 --> 01:25:58.290
charge whatever they want.

01:25:58.290 --> 01:26:00.140
Now, of course, American
company's defense

01:26:00.140 --> 01:26:03.950
is to say, well, that's
why we have to make

01:26:03.950 --> 01:26:06.350
more money from Americans.

01:26:06.350 --> 01:26:07.830
- So we can subsidize the UK?

01:26:07.830 --> 01:26:08.330
- Right.

01:26:12.422 --> 01:26:13.280
- OK, thank you.

01:26:15.990 --> 01:26:17.460
- Hi, I'm Bria Dunham.

01:26:17.460 --> 01:26:19.380
And I'm faculty at
Balton University

01:26:19.380 --> 01:26:21.600
and the Director of our
Undergraduate Health Science

01:26:21.600 --> 01:26:22.560
program.

01:26:22.560 --> 01:26:25.890
You all acknowledged some of the
political thorniness involved

01:26:25.890 --> 01:26:29.190
in moving from where we are
now to a single payer system,

01:26:29.190 --> 01:26:30.870
whatever form that takes.

01:26:30.870 --> 01:26:33.390
And I was wondering if
you see any way forward

01:26:33.390 --> 01:26:36.180
through that thorniness
that is attuned to issues

01:26:36.180 --> 01:26:38.370
of reproductive
justice, particularly

01:26:38.370 --> 01:26:42.970
in the form of securing
publicly funded abortions.

01:26:42.970 --> 01:26:43.470
- Exactly.

01:26:43.470 --> 01:26:46.290
Two things, one is
SB 562 does that.

01:26:46.290 --> 01:26:48.990
We publicly fund abortions,
but more interestingly,

01:26:48.990 --> 01:26:52.080
so does S 1804,
the Sanders bill.

01:26:52.080 --> 01:26:54.480
It actually overturns
the Hyde Amendment.

01:26:54.480 --> 01:26:57.540
And it's quite unique because
the other single payer bill

01:26:57.540 --> 01:27:00.590
in Congress doesn't do that.

01:27:00.590 --> 01:27:03.090
And that was a conscious
policy decision.

01:27:03.090 --> 01:27:04.770
That it would be--
it was assumed

01:27:04.770 --> 01:27:06.780
to be easier politically
not to do it,

01:27:06.780 --> 01:27:09.967
but it was not acceptable
as policy to do it.

01:27:09.967 --> 01:27:11.550
And so, we think
it's very significant

01:27:11.550 --> 01:27:14.850
that both the California and
that federal bill go right

01:27:14.850 --> 01:27:17.182
and say, yes, we're going
to cover reproductive health

01:27:17.182 --> 01:27:18.390
services, including abortion.

