they're on Medicaid.

01:30:16.950 --> 01:30:17.970
We have MassHealth.

01:30:17.970 --> 01:30:20.790
We have Kynect, Medi-cal.

01:30:20.790 --> 01:30:22.560
That's a branding problem.

01:30:22.560 --> 01:30:24.990
We also have,
apparently, hundreds

01:30:24.990 --> 01:30:28.870
of legislators who don't
know what these programs are.

01:30:28.870 --> 01:30:31.560
They don't know what
the programs cover,

01:30:31.560 --> 01:30:35.850
like long term care or opioid
treatment, who is covered,

01:30:35.850 --> 01:30:39.360
disabled children, and as they
discovered, not just low income

01:30:39.360 --> 01:30:42.900
individuals, but also
much of the middle class.

01:30:42.900 --> 01:30:48.660
They also discovered that
the importance of the ACA,

01:30:48.660 --> 01:30:52.470
and of Medicaid, as
fundamental economic pillars

01:30:52.470 --> 01:30:56.370
of many of our communities, as
employers, and also because,

01:30:56.370 --> 01:30:59.520
as Dr. Benjamin noted, that
a healthy population makes

01:30:59.520 --> 01:31:01.830
good business sense.

01:31:01.830 --> 01:31:03.570
And so, for all
of these reasons,

01:31:03.570 --> 01:31:06.720
I think our legislators
heard this summer when

01:31:06.720 --> 01:31:10.460
citizens rose up to protest.

01:31:10.460 --> 01:31:13.430
We also talked about
some paradigm shifts.

01:31:13.430 --> 01:31:16.910
We talked about the current
fragmented system that's

01:31:16.910 --> 01:31:22.500
risen from our industrialized,
market driven medicine

01:31:22.500 --> 01:31:26.570
that leaves us with high
administrative costs, high drug

01:31:26.570 --> 01:31:29.180
costs, and an imbalance
between specialists

01:31:29.180 --> 01:31:30.980
and primary care
that would really

01:31:30.980 --> 01:31:33.130
lead to an improvement
in public health.

01:31:33.130 --> 01:31:37.040
And that we may have $1
trillion wasted every year.

01:31:37.040 --> 01:31:40.070
That is quite a number.

01:31:40.070 --> 01:31:42.560
We're talking about
a paradigm shift,

01:31:42.560 --> 01:31:46.100
one that emphasizes
prevention over treatment,

01:31:46.100 --> 01:31:48.800
and one that really
recognizes the profound social

01:31:48.800 --> 01:31:50.450
determinants of health.

01:31:50.450 --> 01:31:53.870
We heard, in the first panel,
about Boston Medical Center's

01:31:53.870 --> 01:31:57.680
programs to work with the
community on food pantries,

01:31:57.680 --> 01:32:00.950
on housing, on jump
rope challenges.

01:32:00.950 --> 01:32:03.710
But Kate Walsh also
said they can't

01:32:03.710 --> 01:32:08.570
be all things to all
people, which brings us back

01:32:08.570 --> 01:32:12.710
to the question of who's
responsible and of citizenship.

01:32:12.710 --> 01:32:15.600
We examined citizenship
at many levels.

01:32:15.600 --> 01:32:19.310
We talked about states as
citizens in the federal system,

01:32:19.310 --> 01:32:21.200
and that the federalist
system itself

01:32:21.200 --> 01:32:25.460
can be leveraged so that
states can test adaptations

01:32:25.460 --> 01:32:30.270
as proof of concept and
as political strategy.

01:32:30.270 --> 01:32:32.270
So for example, we
had Romney care here

01:32:32.270 --> 01:32:34.250
in Massachusetts
that was something

01:32:34.250 --> 01:32:36.140
of a model for Obamacare.

01:32:36.140 --> 01:32:39.380
And California, I hope, can
hit the ball home for us

01:32:39.380 --> 01:32:42.950
and really inspire the
rest of the nation.

01:32:42.950 --> 01:32:46.340
But we also talked
about political economy

01:32:46.340 --> 01:32:49.220
and political reality
and some sour grapes.

01:32:49.220 --> 01:32:51.560
And Dr. Hsiao gave
us a dose of reality

01:32:51.560 --> 01:32:55.100
that there are very
powerful, vested interests

01:32:55.100 --> 01:32:57.226
behind these choices.

01:32:57.226 --> 01:32:58.850
I thought this was
an interesting point

01:32:58.850 --> 01:33:04.650
that there are many small
winners across the citizenry,

01:33:04.650 --> 01:33:07.600
but a few very powerful losers.

01:33:07.600 --> 01:33:11.340
And because of this, everybody
needs to be mobilized,

01:33:11.340 --> 01:33:12.300
educated.

01:33:12.300 --> 01:33:16.230
Everybody needs to learn
what is at stake as voters

01:33:16.230 --> 01:33:19.500
who hold our legislators
accountable, as employers,

01:33:19.500 --> 01:33:24.640
as healthcare professionals,
as academics, and as advocates.

01:33:24.640 --> 01:33:27.520
Different sectors, the
only way we can do this

01:33:27.520 --> 01:33:29.470
is for different
sectors to come together

01:33:29.470 --> 01:33:32.020
to solve these problems
to elevate health

01:33:32.020 --> 01:33:34.630
as a shared value that
reflects our commitment

01:33:34.630 --> 01:33:38.469
as a nation to justice,
equality, and democracy.

01:33:38.469 --> 01:33:40.510
And with that, I thank
all our panels from today.

01:33:40.510 --> 01:33:42.343
And I thank you for
your fabulous attendance

01:33:42.343 --> 01:33:44.100
and questions.

